# COOPERATIVE BOUNDARY FRAMEWORK v0.1
(Continuation Framework — Coexistence Systems Layer)

Author: Kok Pian Gew  
Date: 2026  
Status: Conceptual Draft (v0.1)

---

## 1. PURPOSE

This framework defines:

> **the conditions under which cooperation between agents remains viable, stable, and capable of continuation.**

It identifies the structural boundaries beyond which:

- coordination fails  
- trust signals lose meaning  
- cooperation collapses or becomes extractive  

This is not a behavioural or moral framework.

It is a **system-level constraint framework** governing the viability of cooperative systems.

---

## 2. POSITION IN FRAMEWORK STACK

This framework sits within:

Continuation  
→ Coexistence Systems  
→ **Cooperative Boundary Framework**

It provides constraints that apply to:

- Trust (interpretation mechanism)  
- Temporal Coordination (intertemporal alignment)  
- Institutional Structures (implementation systems)  

---

## 3. CORE DEFINITION

> **The cooperative boundary is the set of conditions within which coordinated action between agents remains stable, meaningful, and capable of continuation.**

Outside this boundary:

- signals become unreliable  
- coordination breaks down  
- extraction or collapse dominates  

---

## 4. NATURE OF THE FRAMEWORK

The Cooperative Boundary Framework is:

- descriptive — explains when cooperation fails or survives  
- structural — defines system-level constraints  
- non-normative — does not prescribe moral behaviour  

---

## 5. FAILURE MODES OF COOPERATION

Cooperative systems fail when one or more of the following occur:

### 5.1 Signal Collapse
- contribution signals lose meaning or reliability  
- attribution becomes untrustworthy  

---

### 5.2 Coordination Breakdown
- agents cannot align actions  
- expectations become inconsistent  

---

### 5.3 Extraction Dominance
- value is systematically removed without corresponding contribution  
- participation incentives deteriorate  

---

### 5.4 Systemic Instability
- feedback loops amplify noise or volatility  
- system cannot sustain equilibrium  

---

### 5.5 Participation Erosion
- agents disengage  
- contribution capacity remains unused  

---

---

## 6. CORE BOUNDARY PRINCIPLES

The following principles define necessary conditions for cooperative viability.

---

### 6.1 Stability–Exploration Separation Principle

> **A cooperative system must separate stability and exploration into distinct structures to allow adaptation without destabilising the core system.**

Implication:

- core system remains reliable and predictable  
- exploration occurs in bounded, non-disruptive environments  
- transition from exploration to core occurs through controlled mechanisms  

Failure mode:

- uncontrolled experimentation corrupts signals and destabilises coordination  

---

---

### 6.2 Signal Integrity Principle

> **Contribution signals must remain verifiable, interpretable, and resistant to inflation or manipulation.**

Implication:

- attribution must reflect real outcomes  
- signal noise must be controlled  
- credibility depends on signal reliability  

Failure mode:

- signal inflation → loss of trust → coordination collapse  

---

---

### 6.3 Contribution–Reward Coherence Principle

> **Rewards must remain meaningfully linked to verified contribution.**

Implication:

- sustained participation requires perceived fairness  
- value extraction without contribution destabilises the system  

Failure mode:

- disconnection between effort and reward → disengagement  

---

---

### 6.4 Circulation Balance Principle

> **Participation capacity and economic activity must circulate at a rate consistent with coordination and verification capacity.**

Implication:

- under-circulation → stagnation  
- over-circulation → signal degradation  

Failure mode:

- imbalance leads to either inactivity or noise-driven instability  

---

---

### 6.5 Governance Boundedness Principle

> **System-level changes must occur within bounded, controlled mechanisms to prevent destabilising shifts.**

Implication:

- changes are gradual  
- system integrity is preserved  
- coordination expectations remain stable  

Failure mode:

- uncontrolled change → system volatility → loss of trust  

---

---

### 6.6 Continuation Constraint Principle

> **All cooperative systems must remain within operational, economic, and structural limits that allow continuation over time.**

Implication:

- systems must remain viable  
- unsustainable configurations must be corrected or exited  

Failure mode:

- ignoring continuation constraints → collapse  

---

---

## 7. INTERACTION OF PRINCIPLES

These principles are interdependent.

For example:

- signal integrity supports trust  
- circulation balance preserves signal integrity  
- bounded governance protects stability  
- stability–exploration separation enables adaptation  

---

> **Failure in one dimension can propagate across the system.**

---

## 8. RELATIONSHIP TO OTHER FRAMEWORKS

### Trust Framework

- operates within the cooperative boundary  
- depends on signal integrity and contribution coherence  

---

### Temporal Coordination

- operates across time within the boundary  
- depends on stable expectations and credible signals  

---

### Institutional Structure

- implements these boundary conditions in practice  
- enforces constraints through governance, allocation, and design  

---

---

## 9. INTERPRETATION

This framework does not define:

- what agents should value  
- what outcomes are morally desirable  

It defines:

> **what conditions must hold for cooperation to remain possible**

---

---

## 10. CORE FORMULATION

> **Cooperation remains viable only when contribution signals are reliable, rewards remain linked to contribution, system changes are bounded, participation circulates appropriately, and exploration is separated from stable operation under continuation constraints.**

